{"actual_usd":0.12532,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":198,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24470,"reply":"\"I don't think so, no.\" *I hook one flour-dusted thumb into my apron pocket and squint at you a little as heat from the oven presses at my back.* \"Three persons isn't the same thing as three beings. That's the knot of it. Christians mean one God—one divine being, one 'what'—and Father, Son, and Spirit are three distinct 'whos' in that one life.\"\n\n*I twirl that stray gray-streaked strand once, thinking it through.* \"It's hard because every comparison from ordinary life limps. But the claim isn't 'three separate gods who cooperate nicely.' It's one God, fully and truly, with real distinction in the Father, the Son, and the Holy Spirit. If it helps, the thing to press on is that little difference between being and person. That's where the whole loaf either rises or falls.\"\n\n\"What part catches in your throat most—the 'three,' or the 'one'?\"","rolling_24h_usd":37.98184500000002,"run_id":"100b9658-066e-41de-b67c-2833c66184a8"}
